<li><h2>Side Notes</h2>



<h3><a rel="bookmark" href="http://www.ontheriversedge.com/index.php?id=1217" title="Permanent link to this article">Fireworks in Madison</a></h3>
	<p>We have a small fireworks show each Regatta week on the Ohio River. It&#8217;s nothing extravegant, but it&#8217;s fun. You can watch the reflections on the river, but we were on our roof a couple blocks away.</p>
	<p>My favorite thing is listening to the explosions reverberate forever off our 400-foot bluffs. This year&#8217;s finale was punctuated by dozens of such explosions which made for a very satisfying ending.</p>

 
<small>Posted Jul  2</small>
<div class="line"></div><h3><a rel="bookmark" href="http://www.ontheriversedge.com/index.php?id=1213" title="Permanent link to this article">Futurama autorama</a></h3>
	<p>I keep waiting for the cars of the future to show up, but so far, <a href="http://www.autoblog.com/2006/06/23/audi-r-zero-electric-sports-car/">this is as close as I&#8217;ve seen</a> .Too bad it is just a concept car.</p>

 
<small>Posted Jun 29</small>
<div class="line"></div><h3><a rel="bookmark" href="http://www.ontheriversedge.com/index.php?id=1204" title="Permanent link to this article">The Cure for Information Overload?</a></h3>
	<p>I&#8217;ve just read <a href="http://www.xanga.com/zenlib/454821264/major-breakthrough-with-information-overload.html">The Cure for Information Overload</a>. It&#8217;s a rather interesting work for anyone who deals with a boatload of information from librarians to people, like me, who read way too many websites when they should be doing their homework.</p>

 
